      "fullsize": "https://cdn.bsky.app/img/feed_fullsize/plain/did:plc:hu35oubkccqrxl4ldgczpgw7/bafkreibv5vhkkpb3waqncnxhibgrrcgpwtp3xadwcae52ibiiloals6t3i",
      "alt": "The Comintern's Third Period (1928-1934) was a doctrine that declared capitalism in its final death-spiral, which meant that any accommodation with non-communist left forces was tantamount to treason. The Social Democrats - who actually held significant working-class support - were rebranded \"social fascists,\" treated as more dangerous enemies than the actual fascists because they provided a moderate alternative that might stabilize capitalism and prevent the revolutionary rupture. The logic was: the worse things get, the closer the revolution; therefore anyone who ameliorates conditions delays the revolution; therefore reformists are objectively counterrevolutionary.\nThe result was that the German Communist Party spent the early 1930s in vicious conflict with the Social Democrats while Hitler consolidated power.",
